<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">to serve yourself<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  In short they understand that in every single circumstance th<span class="DelHand-author">an</span><span class="AddHand-author">ey</span> <span class="AddHand-author">are</span> to have something in the shape of an Equiva<span class="AddHand-editors">[lent.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">They have a peculiar way for roasting meat.  The roast is suspended with a cord directly over the fire.  A person who sits by with a stick keeps it in continual motion by pushing it to and fro.  When one side is done it is turned up or eaten and the other side Exposed to the same operation.  Meat prepared in this manner tastes much better than that which is done <span class="AddHand-author">in</span> the common way.  The weather was excessively hot all this day.  The natives are afflicted with the hooping cough which carries off them daily.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Monday 21</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">This morning set off on horseback with part of our people towards the upper villages.  Passed several extensive plantations of Corn beans &amp;<sup>c</sup> there were <span class="AddHand-author">women</span> and children hoeing weeding &amp;<sup>c</sup>.  The hoes are made of the shoulder blades of Buffaloes fastened to crooked stakes for handles.  Our road for a while conducted us over Steep hills and deep Vallies then ove<span class="AddHand-author">r</span> a level plain for two miles when we came to the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Soulier Village</span>.</p>
